sition [encoder_type-2] is the first zero = where B goes\n    //\n    // For HDB3 (ET=3): V at [0], zeros at [1], B at [1] -> B00V? No.\n    //   Actually for ET=3, there are 3 zeros before V (positions [1],[2] in SR\n    //   plus [encoder_type-1] which is about to shift out).\n    //   Wait, encoder_type=3 means 3+1=4 zeros get replaced (HDB3 replaces 4 zeros).\n    //   No! encoder_type=3 means HDB3 which replaces 4 consecutive zeros.\n    //   The zero counter goes 0,1,2,3 and triggers at count==3 (encoder_type-1=2? No.)\n    //   \n    //   Let me re-read: encoder_type=3 for HDB3. HDB3 replaces 4 consecutive zeros.\n    //   So the counter should count to 4 (or 3 if 0-indexed).\n    //   In my code: zcount starts at 0, increments on each zero.\n    //   Triggers when zcount == encoder_type - 1 = 2.\n    //   That means it triggers after 3 zeros (count 0,1,2 -> trigger on 3rd zero).\n    //   But HDB3 should trigger after 4 zeros!\n    //\n    //   WAIT. encoder_type=3 for HDB3. The spec says:\n    //   "Select encoding type: 3 for HDB3, 2 for HDB2/B3ZS"\n    //   HDB3 replaces 4 consecutive zeros. HDB2/B3ZS replaces 3.\n    //   So the replacement length is encoder_type + 1.\n    //   Counter should trigger at encoder_type (not encoder_type-1)!\n\n    // CORRECTION: The zero counter should trigger after encoder_type+1 zeros\n    // (HDB3=4 zeros, HDB2=3 zeros). Let me fix Stage 2.\n\n    // Actually wait, let me re-read the spec more carefully:\n    // "HDB3: Replaces every 4 consecutive zeros with either "000V" or "B00V""\n    // "HDB2/B3ZS: Replaces every 3 consecutive zeros with "B0V""\n    // encoder_type=3 -> 4 zeros, encoder_type=2 -> 3 zeros\n    // So replacement length = encoder_type + 1? No, 3+1=4 ✓, 2+1=3 ✓.\n    // The counter counts encoder_type zeros before the V.\n    // In "000V": 3 zeros then V. In "B00V": B then 2 zeros then V.\n    // The V is the (encoder_type+1)th position.\n    // But in my code, the V itself is counted as the trigger point.\n    // The counter sees 0,0,0,0 and on the 4th zero, replaces it with V.\n    // So trigger when zcount == encoder_type (value 3 for HDB3).\n    // zcount: 0->1->2->3 == encoder_type -> trigger.\n    // That means the V replaces the 4th zero. The 3 preceding zeros\n    // are at SR positions [1],[2],[3] when V enters at [0].\n    // B goes at position [encoder_type-1] = [2] for HDB3.\n    // Wait, for "B00V" with HDB3: B,0,0,V.\n    // B is at position encoder_type-1 = 2 in the SR when V enters at 0.\n    // Actually B is the first of the 4 positions. If V enters at [0],\n    // the 3rd zero (before V) is at [1], 2nd at [2], 1st at [3].\n    // So B should be at [3] = [encoder_type]. But SR is only encoder_type deep!\n    // \n    // I think the SR needs to be encoder_type+1 deep, or I need to\n    // handle this differently.\n\n    // Let me redesign. The replacement pattern for HDB3 is:\n    //   000V or B00V (4 positions total)\n    // The SR needs to be encoder_type deep (3 for HDB3) to buffer\n    // the 3 zeros before V. When V is detected:\n    //   - SR contains the 3 preceding zeros at [0],[1],[2]\n    //   - B goes at [2] (the first zero = oldest in SR)\n    //   - But [2] is about to be shifted out this clock!\n    //   - Actually, the shift and V insertion happen simultaneously.\n    //   - After shift: [0]=V, [1]=3rd zero, [2]=2nd zero\n    //   - The 1st zero was at [2] before shift and moves to output.\n    //   - So we can\'t insert B retroactively - it already left!\n    //\n    // Solution: Make SR encoder_type+1 deep. Then:\n    //   Before shift: [0]=3rd zero, [1]=2nd zero, [2]=1st zero, [3]=bit before\n    //   After shift: [0]=V, [1]=3rd zero, [2]=2nd zero, [3]=1st zero\n    //   B insertion: set [3]=1 (the 1st zero becomes B)\n    //   Output: [encoder_type] = [3] = B (or original 1st zero)\n    //   But this adds 1 more pipeline stage.\n    //\n    // Alternative: Make SR encoder_type deep and fix the trigger point.\n    // If trigger is 